				<td colspan="2"><span>Jaroll,
<br />

<br />
Don't get me wrong.  I would like more feedback and more attention devoted to our class.  But lets understand the reality of the situation.  SoE is a corporation that is out to make as much money with the smallest overhead possible.
<br />

<br />
Expansions (new versions of software) make more money than bug fixes.  Bug fixes are required to keep the customer.  There's a point where bug fixes stop and expansions need to come out.
<br />

<br />
Have we reached that point?  SoE believes so.  That business decision may loose customers but that loss may not be as much as is gained by new sales.
<br />

<br />
No where did they say they would fix anything on the top 10 list.  In fact, they didn't even say they would address the issues.  The correspondents pushed hard for them to give any feedback.  They have fixed some stuff (not much bard stuff though).
<br />

<br />
Also, they have added a lot of features, changes &amp; fixes based on information they aquired through the summit.  Take a look at the list they generated from the summit and see how many items they addressed.  Take a look at the last few patch messages and see how many items where patched becuase of community input.
<br />

<br />
I would hardly call that a &quot;bait and switch.&quot;  
<br />

<br />
