				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Bard Issues Updated<a name="60047"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Sep 2 04 10:17 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">All items that would take less than 5 minutes each to address: 
<br />

<br />
1. Alter the % chance to recover from a missed note in the AAs. DONE. 
<br />
I mean come on... We went from never missing a note in one patch to missing notes like a 5th grade band the next. 
<br />

<br />
4. Open up the item database, make LDoN augs that don't suck (1.8 or higher - currently only Brass fits the bill but it is a lousy TYPE 3... Some Type 7 and Type 8 ones would be welcome), stick them in a vendor. DONE. 
<br />

<br />
5. Tweak one line in the Puretone code: MODIFIER_BONUS = 28; changed to MODIFIER_BONUS = 34; DONE. 
<br />

<br />
7. Open up the AA code for these and increase it to where the Gates instruments actually mean something. DONE. 
<br />

<br />
Granted some of the other issues would take some time. Either time spent discussing whether or not its even a good idea to do (IE give Bards the ability to Taunt) or time spent figuring out how to do it (IE autotwist, fix the &quot;song start, song ends&quot;). </span></blockquote> I've been a software developer for over 11 years.  In a real company, developers are not allowed to change functionality of code without the requirements changing.  Changing requirements/functionality of a product takes time.
<br />

<br />
Secondly, if you changed one line of code that signficantly changed functionality, you're not done.  You still have to unit test it and then it has to be QA'd.  The idea that it takes 5 minutes to change code is ludicrious at best.  While it may take 5 minutes to open up the file, check it out of source safe, type the characters in, compile and check it back in, that's not the only aspect of making code changes unless you're working on a 300 line program for a high school project.  Real world software takes more time.
<br />

<br />
SoE may not want to give us these improvements.  We think it would benefit our class and the game in general.  That is <b>our</b> opinion which may not be what SoE wants.
<br />

<br />
Describing code changes as you've layed out above is very amaturish.  You don't know what the code looks like.  You can't say &quot;just open up 1 file and tweak this variable.&quot;  I don't know what the code looks like, so it may be that simple, though my years of experaince makes me doubt that.  It's real easy to say things like &quot;make the mobs realize they are being kited&quot; but in actual practice, it's very difficult.
<br />

<br />
If they make any changes to bards, I hope they spend more than 5 minutes working the code.  If they don't, I bet you can expect to see selos broken for a week after the release of OoW.  Is that what you really want?</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
